So if they get 3 right (their score is 3) then one wrong (their score drops to 2), they would then need to get 3 more right in a row to reach a score of 5 (even though they got 6 right and 1 wrong). This is good for three reasons. First, it always gives a student a chance to reach a grade of 100% even if they make a mistake. Second, it forces the students to improve their accuracy rate to at least better than 50% in order to make progress. Third, students who are struggling will have to spend more time completing the assignment to reach the \u201crequired\u201d amount, which is probably much needed practice for those who struggle, while the students who know it already can do 1,2,3,4,5 and be done quickly since they don\u2019t need to spend more time. It also teaches the students the importance of checking their work and being careful not to submit incorrect answers because the \u201cpenalty\u201d will require additional time and work to fix. \n\t'),d.ec(2,"br"),d.ec(3,"br"),d.dd(4,"\n\tThe teacher can edit the penalty, however. You can set the penalty to \u201cno penalty\u201d which would mean they only had to get 5 right even if they got 30 wrong in between. You can also set the \u201cpenalty\u201d lower, to 0.5 for example, meaning they only lose a half a point for each wrong answer, effectively meaning they only lose a point for every two wrong answers. This could be beneficial for students who are feeling too frustrated and are giving up. We trust teachers to know their own students and set the \u201crequired\u201d and \u201cpenalty\u201d appropriately for their students. The issue with \u201cno penalty\u201d is that a student can simply submit a blank answer for a question that looks \u201chard\u201d and search for \u201ceasy\u201d ones, which may be sending the wrong message and hurting student\u2019s chances to experience challenging questions. \n\t"),d.ec(5,"br"),d.ec(6,"br"),d.dd(7,"\n\tIt is recommended to watch the 2nd and 3rd videos (at least) in the ?
